Subject:    <a href="?t=95837892400002&r=1&w=2">Re: Why Germany lies about the DE. domain.</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837817000038&r=1&w=2">mcsun!unido!fauern!fauern!eckert () uunet ! uu ! net  (Toerless Eckert)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=199005">1990-05-18 14:15:28</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326997&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326997&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

&gt;From article &lt;1608@mcsun.eu.net&gt;, by dfk@eu.net (Daniel Karrenberg):
&gt; eckert@medusa.informatik.uni-erlangen.de (Toerless Eckert) writes:
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;There are no advantages in using alternate DE servers to uunet with
&gt;&gt;the current scheme. The problem that must be solved in this respect is
&gt;&gt;to allow non US connected networks into the DNS (especially the
&gt;&gt;IN-ADDR.ARPA zones). If that is done, we may well drop the current
&gt;&gt;scheme and have one common DE zone.
&gt; 
&gt; For the .de zone there is no problem at all. Just include all data even
&gt; for hosts and sites without connectivity. Who is going to stop you?
&gt; On what grounds?

No, it's a design decision, This way we can have different MX
records in the DE zone in the states, and the german one (surely
nearly the same effect can be reached by adding more MX records
to one zone, but then you might end up sending mail from germany to germany
through the states, if something is not running correctly,
something which happens rather often around here).

Anyway, i don't see the need for discussion here: it doesn't make a
difference for anyone that the zones are different, or does it - No,
it does not, as those who can't resolve domainnames from the states
couldn't even reach the associated nets in germany.

-- 

Toerless Eckert          | /C=de/A=dbp/P=uni-erlangen/OU=informatik/S=eckert
Systemadministrator TI59 | X.400 ^ Internet&gt; eckert@informatik.uni-erlangen.de

